\begin{abstract}
	We present QuantumViz, a Python library for quantum algorithm visualization. QuantumViz provides five visualization tools: Bloch Sphere for single-qubit states, State City for density matrices, Circuit Diagrams for quantum gates, Cost Landscapes for optimization surfaces, and Dynamic Flow for time evolution. The software is available via \texttt{pip install quantumviz} and supports quantum algorithms including Grover's search, QAOA, VQE, QFT, and Rabi oscillation. This codebase release includes documentation, API reference, example applications, and benchmarking tests. We provide guidelines for selecting appropriate visualization techniques based on algorithm family: Oracle-based algorithms benefit from Bloch Sphere + State City, Transform-based from State City, Variational from Cost Landscapes + Circuit Diagrams, and Simulation-based from Dynamic Flow.

	\bigskip
	\textbf{Keywords:} Quantum Computing, Algorithm Visualization, Python, Bloch Sphere, Density Matrix, Cost Landscape
\end{abstract}

\newpage

\section{Introduction}

Quantum computing leverages superposition, entanglement, and interference to solve problems intractable for classical computers. As quantum hardware matures and quantum algorithms become more sophisticated, the need for effective visualization techniques becomes paramount. Understanding quantum algorithm behavior requires representing complex states and operations in intuitive formats.

Existing quantum computing libraries such as QuTiP, Qiskit, and Cirq provide some visualization capabilities, but they focus on general-purpose state and circuit visualization without algorithm-specific optimization. This paper presents QuantumViz, a Python library specifically designed for visualizing quantum algorithm internals based on algorithm family.

QuantumViz provides five visualization tools:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Bloch Sphere}: Single-qubit geometric representation
	\item \textbf{State City}: Density matrix bar chart visualization
	\item \textbf{Circuit Diagram}: Quantum gate circuit rendering
	\item \textbf{Cost Landscape}: Optimization surface visualization
	\item \textbf{Dynamic Flow}: Time evolution trajectory plotting
\end{itemize}

The software is available via \texttt{pip install quantumviz} and supports Python 3.9+. This codebase release (v\version) includes installation instructions, API documentation, example applications, and benchmarking tests.

\subsection{Software Availability}

QuantumViz is released under the MIT license and available from GitHub:
\begin{itemize}
	\item GitHub: \url{https://github.com/QuantumVisualization/quantumviz}
\end{itemize}

This release includes source code, test suite, and user guide. The current version is v\version, released \releasedate.

