\section{Benchmarking}

\subsection{Performance Benchmarks}

Our results strongly support the hypothesis that certain visualization styles are optimal for specific algorithm families.

\begin{enumerate}
	\item \textbf{Oracle-based algorithms}: Confirmed. Bloch Sphere reveals the geometric rotation mechanism, while State City quantifies probability amplification. Circuit diagrams provide structural context.

	\item \textbf{Transform-based algorithms}: Confirmed. State City is essential because it reveals phase periodicity in the density matrix imaginary part—information that Bloch Sphere cannot capture for multi-qubit systems.

	\item \textbf{Variational algorithms}: Confirmed. Circuit diagrams show ansatz structure and parameter placement, while Cost Landscapes reveal the optimization landscape. Bloch Sphere provides minimal insight.

	\item \textbf{Simulation-based algorithms}: Confirmed. Dynamic Flow and trajectory visualizations are essential for understanding Hamiltonian time evolution.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Usage Guidelines}

Based on our findings, we provide the following guidelines:

\begin{table}[h!]
	\centering
	\caption{Recommended Visualizations by Algorithm Family}
	\label{tab:guidelines}
	\begin{tabular}{@{}ll@{}}
		\toprule
		\textbf{Algorithm Family} & \textbf{Recommended Visualizations} \\ \midrule
		Oracle-based              & Bloch Sphere + State City + Circuit \\
		Transform-based           & State City + Circuit                \\
		Variational               & Circuit + Cost Landscape            \\
		Simulation-based          & Dynamic Flow + Bloch Trajectory     \\ \bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Trade-offs and Limitations}

\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Bloch Sphere}: Limited to single-qubit states; cannot represent entanglement
	\item \textbf{State City}: Excellent insight but impractical for 5+ qubits due to exponential matrix growth ($2^n \times 2^n$)
	\item \textbf{Cost Landscape}: Requires parameter sweep computation (O($n^2$) parameters)
	\item \textbf{Dynamic Flow}: Static images; animation would improve understanding
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Functional Tests}

QuantumViz includes a test suite covering core functionality:

\begin{itemize}
	\item \texttt{test\_bloch\_sphere.py}: Tests for single-qubit state plotting
	\item \texttt{test\_state\_city.py}: Tests for density matrix visualization
	\item \texttt{test\_circuit\_diagram.py}: Tests for circuit rendering
	\item \texttt{test\_cost\_landscape.py}: Tests for optimization landscapes
	\item \texttt{test\_dynamic\_flow.py}: Tests for time evolution
	\item \texttt{test\_cli.py}: Tests for command-line interface
\end{itemize}

Run tests with: \texttt{pytest tests/}

\subsection{Limitations}

\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Bloch Sphere}: Limited to single-qubit states; cannot represent entanglement
	\item \textbf{State City}: Impractical for 5+ qubits due to exponential matrix growth
	\item \textbf{Cost Landscape}: Requires parameter sweep computation
	\item \textbf{Real hardware}: Testing on classical simulation only
\end{itemize}

Future work will address these limitations.

\newpage

\section{Conclusions}

We have presented QuantumViz, a Python library for quantum algorithm visualization. This codebase release (v\version) provides five visualization tools tested across four algorithm families. Our key findings are:

\begin{enumerate}
	\item \textbf{Oracle-based algorithms} (Grover's, Deutsch-Jozsa) benefit from Bloch Sphere + State City
	\item \textbf{Transform-based algorithms} (QFT, QPE) require State City for phase visualization
	\item \textbf{Variational algorithms} (QAOA, VQE) need Cost Landscapes + Circuit Diagrams
	\item \textbf{Simulation-based algorithms} (Rabi, Ising) are best understood via Dynamic Flow
	\item \textbf{Scalability}: State City practical to ~4 qubits; others scale to 10+ qubits
\end{enumerate}

These findings provide practical guidance for selecting visualization techniques based on algorithm family.

\subsection{Future Work}

\begin{itemize}
	\item Conduct larger user study (n $\ge$ 30) to validate visualization guidelines statistically
	\item Develop hybrid visualizations combining multiple techniques
	\item Implement interactive/animated visualizations
	\item Extend to 10+ qubit systems with sparse representations
	\item Add real quantum hardware output visualization
\end{itemize}

